# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uds-diagnostics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:uds-diagnostics/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:uds-diagnostics/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] In the OSI model, ISO-TP covers the layer 3 (network layer) and 4 (transport layer).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] ISO-TP can be operated with its own addressing as so-called *Extended Addressing* or without address using only the CAN ID (so-called *Normal Addressing*).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Extended addressing uses the first data byte of each frame as an additional element of the address, reducing the application payload by one byte.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] For clarity the protocol description below is based on Normal Addressing with eight byte CAN frames.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] In total, six types of addressing are allowed by the ISO 15765-2 Protocol.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] ISO-TP prepends one or more metadata bytes to the payload data in the eight byte CAN frame, reducing the payload to seven or fewer bytes per frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The metadata is called the Protocol Control Information, or PCI.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The initial field is four bits indicating the frame type, and implicitly describing the PCI length.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] A message of seven bytes or less is sent in a single frame, with the initial byte containing the type (0) and payload length (1-7 bytes).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] With the 0 in the type field, this can also pass as a simpler protocol with a length-data format and is often misinterpreted as such.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] A message longer than 7 bytes requires segmenting the message packet over multiple frames.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] A segmented transfer starts with a First Frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The PCI is two bytes in this case, with the first 4 bit field the type (type 1) and the following 12 bits the message length (excluding the type and length bytes).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The recipient confirms the transfer with a flow control frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The flow control frame has three PCI bytes specifying the interval between subsequent frames and how many consecutive frames may be sent (*Block Size*).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] For CAN FD, the ISO 15765-2 protocol has been extended for Single and First frame, to allow larger size values, but still backwards compatible with traditional ISO 15765.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] <= 127 (0x00 to 0x7F), separation time in milliseconds.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The initial byte contains the type (type = 3) in the first four bits, and a flag in the next four bits indicating if the transfer is allowed (0 = Continue To Send, 1 = Wait, 2 = Overflow/abort).
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The next byte is the block size, the count of frames that may be sent before waiting for the next flow control frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] A value of zero allows the remaining frames to be sent without flow control or delay.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The third byte is the minimum Separation Time (STmin), the minimum delay time between frames.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] STmin values up to 127 (0x7F) specify the minimum number of milliseconds to delay between frames, while values in the range 241 (0xF1) to 249 (0xF9) specify delays increasing from 100 to 900 microseconds.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Note that the Separation Time is defined as the minimum time between the end of one frame to the beginning of the next.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Robust implementations should be prepared to accept frames from a sender that misinterprets this as the frame repetition rate i.e. from start-of-frame to start-of-frame.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Even careful implementations may fail to account for the minor effect of bit-stuffing in the physical layer.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The sender transmits the rest of the message using Consecutive Frames.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Each Consecutive Frame has a one byte PCI, with a four bit type (type = 2) followed by a 4-bit sequence number.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The sequence number starts at 1 and increments with each frame sent (1, 2,..., F, 0, 1,...), with which lost or discarded frames can be detected.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Each consecutive frame starts at 0, initially for the first set of data in the first frame will be considered as 0th data.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] So the first set of CF(Consecutive frames) start from 0x1.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] There afterwards when it reaches 0x2F, will be started from 0x20 (e.g.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] The 12-bit length field (as indicated in the First Frame) allows up to 4095 bytes of user data in a segmented message, but in practice the typical application-specific limit is considerably lower because of receive buffer or hardware limitations.
[src:uds-diagnostics/iso-15765-2] Timing parameters, such as P1 and P2 timers, have to be mentioned.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD systems give the vehicle owner or repair technician access to the status of the various vehicle sub-systems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The amount of diagnostic information available via OBD has varied widely since its introduction in the early 1980s versions of onboard vehicle computers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Early versions of OBD would simply illuminate a tell-tale light if a problem was detected, but would not provide any information as to the nature of the problem.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD implementations use a standardized digital communications port to provide real-time data and diagnostic trouble codes which allow malfunctions within the vehicle to be rapidly identified.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] GM's ALDL (Assembly Line Diagnostic Link) is sometimes referred to as a predecessor to, or a manufacturer's proprietary version of, an OBD-I diagnostic starting in 1981.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This interface was made in different varieties and changed with power train control modules (aka PCM, ECM, ECU).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Different versions had slight differences in pin-outs and baud rates.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Earlier versions used a 160 baud rate, while later versions went up to 8192 baud and used bi-directional communications to the PCM.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The regulatory intent of OBD-I was to encourage auto manufacturers to design reliable emission control systems that remain effective for the vehicle's "useful life".
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The hope was that by forcing annual emissions testing for California starting in 1988, and denying registration to vehicles that did not pass, drivers would tend to purchase vehicles that would more reliably pass the test.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I was largely unsuccessful, as the means of reporting emissions-specific diagnostic information was not standardized.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Technical difficulties with obtaining standardized and reliable emissions information from all vehicles led to an inability to implement the annual testing program effectively.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs) of OBD-I vehicles can usually be found without an expensive scan tool.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Each manufacturer used their own Diagnostic Link Connector (DLC), DLC location, DTC definitions, and procedure to read the DTCs from the vehicle.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] DTCs from OBD-I cars are often read through the blinking patterns of the 'Check Engine Light' (CEL) or 'Service Engine Soon' (SES) light.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] By connecting certain pins of the diagnostic connector, the 'Check Engine' light will blink out a two-digit number that corresponds to a specific error condition.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The DTCs of some OBD-I cars are interpreted in different ways, however.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Cadillac fuel-injected vehicles are equipped with actual *onboard* diagnostics, providing trouble codes, actuator tests and sensor data through the new digital Electronic Climate Control display.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Holding down 'Off' and 'Warmer' for several seconds activates the diagnostic mode without the need for an external scan tool.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some Honda engine computers are equipped with LEDs that light up in a specific pattern to indicate the DTC.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] General Motors, some 1989–1995 Ford vehicles (DCL), and some 1989–1995 Toyota/Lexus vehicles have a live sensor data stream available; however, many other OBD-I equipped vehicles do not.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I vehicles have fewer DTCs available than OBD-II equipped vehicles.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD 1.5 refers to a partial implementation of OBD-II which General Motors used on some vehicles in 1994, 1995 & 1996 (GM did not use the term OBD 1.5 in the documentation for these vehicles — they simply had an OBD and an OBD-II section in the service manual).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For example, the 1994–1995 model year Corvettes have one post-catalyst oxygen sensor (although they have two catalytic converters), and have a subset of the OBD-II codes implemented.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For ALDL connections, pin 9 is the data stream, pins 4 and 5 are ground, and pin 16 is the battery voltage.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 compatible scan tool is required to read codes generated by OBD 1.5.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Additional vehicle-specific diagnostic and control circuits are also available on this connector.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For instance, on the Corvette there are interfaces for the Class 2 serial data stream from the PCM, the CCM diagnostic terminal, the radio data stream, the airbag system, the selective ride control system, the low tire pressure warning system, and the passive keyless entry system.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 has also been used in the Ford Scorpio since 95.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II is an improvement over OBD-I in both capability and standardization.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II standard specifies the type of diagnostic connector and its pinout, the electrical signalling protocols available, and the messaging format.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] It also provides a candidate list of vehicle parameters to monitor along with how to encode the data for each.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] There is a pin in the connector that provides power for the scan tool from the vehicle battery, which eliminates the need to connect a scan tool to a power source separately.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] However, some technicians might still connect the scan tool to an auxiliary power source to protect data in the unusual event that a vehicle experiences a loss of electrical power due to a malfunction.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Finally, the OBD-II standard provides an extensible list of DTCs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] As a result of this standardization, a single device can query the on-board computer(s) in any vehicle.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This OBD-II came in two models OBD-IIA and OBD-IIB.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II standardization was prompted by emissions requirements, and though only emission-related codes and data are required to be transmitted through it, most manufacturers have made the OBD-II Data Link Connector the only one in the vehicle through which all systems are diagnosed and programmed.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II Diagnostic Trouble Codes are 4-digit, preceded by a letter: P for powertrain (engine and transmission), B for body, C for chassis, and U for network.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II specification provides for a standardized hardware interface — the female 16-pin (2x8) J1962 connector, where type A is used for 12-volt vehicles and type B for 24-volt vehicles.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Unlike the OBD-I connector, which was sometimes found under the bonnet of the vehicle, the OBD-II connector is required to be within 2 feet (0.61 m) of the steering wheel (unless an exemption is applied for by the manufacturer, in which case it is still somewhere within reach of the driver).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The assignment of unspecified pins is left to the vehicle manufacturer's discretion.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2000 for petrol and January 1, 2003, for diesel.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For passenger cars with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of greater than 2500 kg and for light commercial vehicles, the regulation dates applied from January 1, 2002, for petrol models, and January 1, 2007, for diesel models.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of EOBD is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] With Euro V and Euro VI emission standards, EOBD emission thresholds are lower than previous Euro III and IV.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Each of the EOBD fault codes consists of five characters: a letter, followed by four numbers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The letter refers to the system being interrogated e.g.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Pxxxx would refer to the powertrain system.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would be a 0 if complies to the EOBD standard.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would refer to the sub system.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The following two characters would refer to the individual fault within each subsystem.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The term "EOBD2" is marketing speak used by some vehicle manufacturers to refer to manufacturer-specific features that are not actually part of the OBD or EOBD standard.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] JOBD is a version of OBD-II for vehicles sold in Japan.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 Vehicle Standard (**A**ustralian **D**esign **R**ule **79/01** – Emission Control for Light Vehicles, 2005) is the Australian equivalent of OBD-II.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] It applies to all vehicles of category M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3,500 kg (7,700 lb) or less, registered from new within Australia and produced since January 1, 2006 for petrol-engined cars and since January 1, 2007 for diesel-engined cars.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2005 for petrol and January 1, 2006, for diesel.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 standard was supplemented by the ADR 79/02 standard which imposed tighter emissions restrictions, applicable to all vehicles of class M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3500 kg or less, from July 1, 2008, for new models, July 1, 2010, for all models.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of this standard is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In North America, EMD and EMD+ are on-board diagnostic systems that were used on vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of 14,000 lb (6,400 kg) or more between the 2007 and 2012 model years if those vehicles did not already implement OBD-II.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was used on California emissions vehicles between model years 2007 and 2009 that did not already have OBD-II.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was required to monitor fuel delivery, exhaust gas recirculation, the diesel particulate filter (on diesel engines), and emissions-related powertrain control module inputs and outputs for circuit continuity, data rationality, and output functionality.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD+ was used on model year 2010-2012 California and Federal petrol-engined vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of over 14,000 lb (6,400 kg), it added the ability to monitor nitrogen oxide catalyst performance.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] EMD and EMD+ are similar to OBD-I in logic but use the same SAE J1962 data connector and CAN bus as OBD-II systems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Five signaling protocols are permitted with the OBD-II interface.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Most vehicles implement only one of the protocols.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] All OBD-II pinouts use the same connector, but different pins are used with the exception of pin 4 (battery ground) and pin 16 (battery positive).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II provides access to data from the engine control unit (ECU) and offers a valuable source of information when troubleshooting problems inside a vehicle.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The SAE J1979 standard defines a method for requesting various diagnostic data and a list of standard parameters that might be available from the ECU.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The various available parameters are addressed by "parameter identification numbers" or **PID**s which are defined in J1979.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of basic PIDs, their definitions, and the formula to convert raw OBD-II output to meaningful diagnostic units, see OBD-II PIDs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Manufacturers are not required to implement all PIDs listed in J1979 and they are allowed to include proprietary PIDs that are not listed.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The PID request and data retrieval system gives access to real time performance data as well as flagged DTCs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of generic OBD-II DTCs suggested by the SAE, see #OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Individual manufacturers often enhance the OBD-II code set with additional proprietary DTCs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Here is a basic introduction to the OBD communication protocol according to ISO 15031.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In SAE J1979 these "modes" were renamed to "services", starting in 2003.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Various tools are available that plug into the OBD connector to access OBD functions.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These range from simple generic consumer-level tools to sophisticated OEM dealership tools and vehicle telematic devices.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] A range of hand-held scan tools is available.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Mobile device applications allow mobile devices such as cell phones and tablets to display and manipulate OBD-II data accessed via USB adaptor cables or Bluetooth adapters plugged into the car's OBD II connector.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Newer devices on the market are equipped with GPS sensors and the ability to transmit vehicle location and diagnostics data over a cellular network.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD-II devices can be used for locating vehicles and monitoring driving behavior in addition to reading Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTC).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices allow users to reset engine DTCs, effectively turning off engine lights in the dashboard; however, resetting the codes does not address the underlying issues and can lead to engine damage if a serious issue is left unattended.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD-II software package, when installed on a computer (Windows, Mac, or Linux), can help diagnose the onboard system, read and erase DTCs, turn off the MIL, show real-time data, and measure vehicle fuel economy.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Using OBD-II software requires an OBD-II adapter (commonly using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi or USB) plugged into the OBD-II port to enable the vehicle to connect with the computer where the software is installed.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] A PC-based OBD analysis tool converts the OBD-II signals to a serial data format (USB or serial port) readable by PCs or Macs.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The software then decodes the received data for visual display.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Many interfaces are based on the ELM327 or STN OBD interpreter ICs, both of which read all five generic OBD-II protocols.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some adapters now use the J2534 API, allowing them to access OBD-II protocols for both cars and trucks.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The extent that a PC tool may access manufacturer- or vehicle-specific ECU diagnostics varies between software products as it does between hand-held scanners.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Data loggers are designed to capture vehicle data while the vehicle is in normal operation for later analysis.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Analysis of vehicle black box data may be performed periodically, automatically transmitted wirelessly to a third party, or retrieved for forensic analysis after an event such as an accident, traffic infringement, or mechanical fault.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In the United States, many states now use OBD-II testing instead of tailpipe testing in OBD-II-compliant vehicles (1996 and newer).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Since OBD-II stores trouble codes for emissions equipment, the testing computer can query the vehicle's onboard computer and verify there are no emission-related trouble codes and that the vehicle is in compliance with emission standards for the model year it was manufactured.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In the Netherlands, 2006 and later vehicles get a yearly EOBD emission check.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Auto enthusiasts have traditionally installed additional gauges such as for manifold vacuum or battery current.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD standard interface has enabled a new generation of enthusiast instrumentation accessing the full range of vehicle data used for diagnostics, as well as derived data such as instantaneous fuel economy.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Instrumentation may take the form of dedicated trip computers, carputers, or interfaces to PDAs, smartphones, or a Garmin navigation unit.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] As a carputer is essentially a PC, the same software could be loaded as for PC-based scan tools and vice versa; the distinction lies in the software's intended use.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These enthusiast systems may also include some functionality similar to the other scan tools.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II information is a data source for fleet telematics systems.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Devices that perform fleet management functions such as fleet tracking, monitoring fuel efficiency, and preventing unsafe driving often connect to the OBD-II port.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The port is also used for remote diagnostics and by pay-as-you-drive insurance.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Hundreds of different hardware manufacturers produce OBD-II telematics devices.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] These devices vary in their capabilities.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Some simpler GPS tracking devices use the OBD-II port only as a convenient source of power.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices, such as a telematic control unit, are able to access the vehicle's internal network to capture and decode a wide range of operational data.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Commonly supported OBD II data such as vehicle speed, RPM, and fuel level allow these devices to monitor vehicle idling times, speeding, and over-revving.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Monitoring OBD II DTCs can alert a company to a vehicle's engine problems by providing the relevant diagnostic code.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Other sensor data from the port can be used to detect unsafe driving in real time.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] This detection is done by adding a complex events processor (CEP) to the backend and on the client's interface.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II is also monitored to block mobile phones when driving and to record trip data for insurance purposes.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes (DTCs) are five characters long, with the first letter indicating a category, and the remaining four being a hexadecimal number.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The first character, representing category can only be one of the following four letters, given here with their associated meanings.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction in number is due to how only two bits of memory are used to indicate the category when DTCs are stored and transmitted).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The second character is a number in the range of 0–3.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction is again due to memory storage limitations).
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The third character may denote a particular vehicle system that the fault relates to.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Finally the fourth and fifth characters define the exact problem detected.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] In 2012, researchers at the University of Washington and University of California examined the security around OBD and found that they were able to gain control over many vehicle components via the interface.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Furthermore, they were able to upload new firmware into the engine control units.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] Their conclusion is that vehicle embedded systems are not designed with security in mind.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] There have been reports of thieves using specialist OBD reprogramming devices to enable them to steal cars without the use of a key.
[src:uds-diagnostics/on-board-diagnostics] The primary causes of this vulnerability lie in the tendency for vehicle manufacturers to extend the bus for purposes other than those for which it was designed, and the lack of authentication and authorization in the OBD specifications, which instead rely largely on security through obscurity.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] The term "unified" refers to the fact that UDS is an international standard rather than a manufacturer-specific protocol.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Today, nearly all Tier 1 suppliers implement UDS in ECUs developed for automotive original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] UDS is also integrated into larger software architectures, including AUTOSAR.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Modern vehicles have a diagnostic interface for on-board diagnostics, which makes it possible to connect a computer (client) or diagnostics tool, which is referred to as tester, to the communication system of the vehicle.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Thus, UDS requests can be sent to the controllers which provide responses (this may be positive or negative).
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Request messages are transmitted by a Client towards one or more Servers.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Service Identifier (SID) is the first byte in each request message.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Response messages are transmitted by Servers to a Client.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] The first byte in the response message is usually Response Service Identifier (RSID) value (with the exception of following responses to ReadDataByPeriodicIdentifier service).
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Format of each positive response message is specific for the diagnostic service it relates to.
[src:uds-diagnostics/unified-diagnostic-services] Negative Response Codes (NRC in short) carry the information for request message rejection.
